  <div class="container page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Index Overlap Explained: S&amp;P 500 vs. Nasdaq vs. Dow Jones</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">A clear breakdown of how America's three most famous stock market benchmarks intersect and diverge.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Every night on the evening news, anchors recite the day's performance for "The Dow, the S&amp;P, and the Nasdaq." If you're new to investing, it's easy to assume these three indices are completely separate buckets of companies. Or, conversely, you might assume that buying the broad S&amp;P 500 means you own everything in the other two. The truth lies somewhere in the middle.</p>

      <p>These indices are the benchmarks against which nearly all U.S. mutual funds and portfolio managers measure their performance. They dictate the flow of trillions of passive index-fund dollars. Understanding how they overlap and how they are constructed is essential for any investor trying to build a diversified portfolio.</p>

      <h2>What the S&amp;P 500 Actually Represents</h2>
      <p>The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 (S&amp;P 500) tracks the performance of 500 large companies listed on stock exchanges in the United States. To be included, a company must be highly liquid, have a massive market capitalization (typically over $18 billion), and demonstrate a history of profitability. Because of these rules, the S&amp;P 500 naturally adjusts its composition over time to capture the shifting weight of the U.S. economy, adding high-growth companies like those that might emerge from the <a href="/acrew-capital-portfolio">Acrew Capital portfolio</a> and dropping laggards.</p>

      <p>The S&amp;P 500 is market-capitalization-weighted, meaning larger companies (like Apple and Microsoft) have a significantly greater impact on the index's movement than smaller ones (like an airline or a regional bank). Because of its strict inclusion rules and broad sector representation, professional investors consider it the most accurate barometer of the U.S. large-cap equity market.</p>

      <h2>The Dow Jones Industrial Average: Price-Weighted Blue Chips</h2>
      <p>The Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJIA) is older and fundamentally different. It tracks just 30 large, publicly-owned companies based in the United States. Unlike the S&amp;P 500, which relies on a mathematical formula for inclusion, the 30 companies in the Dow are hand-picked by an index committee at S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices to represent the broader economy.</p>

      <p>The most confusing aspect of the Dow is its weighting. It is "price-weighted," meaning a stock with a higher per-share price (like a $500 stock) has a much larger impact on the index than a $50 stock, regardless of either company's actual total value. This archaic method is why many modern professionals ignore the Dow in favor of the S&amp;P 500. A company could split its stock, cutting its share price in half without changing its fundamental value, and instantly halve its influence on the Dow.</p>

      <h2>The Nasdaq: An Exchange and an Index</h2>
      <p>The term "Nasdaq" is often used interchangeably to mean two things: the Nasdaq Stock Market (the physical/electronic exchange where stocks trade) and the Nasdaq Composite Index (which tracks over 3,000 stocks listed on that exchange). Furthermore, the Nasdaq-100 tracks the 100 largest non-financial companies listed on the exchange and is heavily skewed toward the technology sector.</p>

      <p>Many people associate the Nasdaq exclusively with technology giants like Amazon, Tesla, and Google, but it also includes biotech startups, regional banks, and even retail chains. The Nasdaq Composite is market-cap-weighted, similar to the S&amp;P 500, but its massive inclusion of over 3,000 companies means it captures thousands of small-cap and unprofitable companies that the S&amp;P 500 ignores.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>The Overlap Formula</strong>
        <p>Because the S&amp;P 500 tracks the largest U.S. companies regardless of the exchange they trade on, it inherently includes many of the same stocks found in the Nasdaq and the Dow.
        <br/><br/>
        <strong>S&amp;P 500 ∩ DJIA:</strong> The S&amp;P 500 includes all 30 Dow stocks.
        <br/>
        <strong>S&amp;P 500 ∩ Nasdaq:</strong> The S&amp;P 500 includes the largest companies listed on the Nasdaq exchange, but ignores thousands of smaller Nasdaq stocks that don't meet its profitability or size criteria.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Why the Overlap Matters</h2>
      <p>Understanding this overlap is crucial for portfolio construction. Many investors buy an S&amp;P 500 index fund, a Dow Jones index fund, and a Nasdaq-100 index fund, believing they are thoroughly diversified. In reality, they are deeply overlapping.</p>

      <p>If you own all three, you are heavily concentrated in the "Magnificent Seven" tech stocks (Apple, Microsoft, Alphabet, Amazon, Nvidia, Meta, and Tesla), because those mega-cap companies dominate the top weightings of the S&amp;P 500 and the Nasdaq-100, and several are also in the Dow.</p>

      <p>The Role of These Indices in Your Portfolio</p>
      <p>Deciding between the S&amp;P 500, Nasdaq, and Dow Jones is less about picking a clear winner and more about understanding what you're buying. For the vast majority of long-term investors, the S&amp;P 500 is the most logical choice as a core holding. It provides a highly diversified slice of the entire U.S. economy, capturing the growth of tech alongside the stability of utilities, healthcare, and consumer staples.</p>

      <p>Some investors choose to tilt their portfolios. For instance, if you have a long time horizon and strongly believe in the continued dominance of the tech sector, you might hold the S&amp;P 500 as your core and add a Nasdaq-100 ETF to overweight your exposure to technology. Conversely, if you prefer dividend-paying, mature companies with less volatility, the Dow Jones might be more appealing, though many prefer dividend-specific ETFs instead of relying on the Dow's quirky price-weighting.</p>

      <p>It is important to remember that venture-backed companies like those found in the <a href="/acrew-capital-portfolio">Acrew Capital Portfolio</a> often strive to one day go public and join indices like the Nasdaq or S&amp;P 500. Additionally, when you evaluate companies from sectors outside of tech, such as those discussed in our guide on <a href="/mining-stocks">mining stocks</a>, you'll see they play a distinct role in balancing the sector weights within the broader S&amp;P 500, offering diversification against heavy tech exposure.</p>

      <h2>Is the S&amp;P 500 the Ultimate Index?</h2>
      <p>For most investors, the S&amp;P 500 is the best core holding because it naturally diversifies across multiple sectors. It includes the major companies that make up the Dow Jones and the most profitable, largest companies from the Nasdaq. The S&amp;P 500 is a "one-stop-shop" for U.S. large-cap equities, but it isn't perfect.</p>

      <p>Because it is market-cap-weighted, a bull run in a specific sector—like technology in recent years—can cause the index to become top-heavy and less diversified than it appears on paper. For this reason, many investors also include mid-cap indices, small-cap indices (like the Russell 2000), and international stock funds in their overall portfolio strategy to cover the gaps the S&amp;P 500 leaves behind.</p>
    </section>

